      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let me break it down for you in a more straightforward way.\n\nA planetary conjunction occurs when two or more planets appear to be aligned in the sky, often with the Sun, Earth, and other planets in close proximity. This alignment happens when the planets are in the same plane of the solar system, which is the plane that contains the Sun and the majority of the planets.\n\nThe actual mechanics of a conjunction involve the positions of the planets and their orbits around the Sun. When two planets are in the same plane and their orbits bring them close to each other, their images appear to overlap in the sky. This is because the Earth is positioned between the Sun and the two planets, and the light from the Sun reflects off the planets, creating the illusion of a conjunction.\n\nThink of it like this: imagine two planets, one on either side of the Sun, with the Earth in between. As the planets move in their orbits, they appear to shift positions in the sky, creating the illusion of a conjunction. The closer the planets are to each other, the more pronounced the conjunction appears.\n\nIn the case of a planetary conjunction, the planets are not actually touching, but rather, their images",
